  <h1>Types of Class Action Cases</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Consumer fraud</h2><p>False advertising, deceptive pricing, undisclosed fees. State consumer protection laws (California UCL, NY GBL) allow class-wide relief without individualized injury proof. Common in food labeling, subscription billing, and mortgage fee cases.</p>
  <h2>Data breach / privacy</h2><p>CCPA, BIPA, and common-law negligence claims. BIPA (Illinois Biometric Information Privacy Act) allows $1,000&ndash;$5,000 statutory damages per violation and has driven some of the largest per-claimant settlements in recent years.</p>
  <h2>Securities fraud</h2><p>Section 10(b) and Rule 10b-5 claims for stock price inflation from material misrepresentations. PSLRA heightened pleading standards filter weak cases. Loss causation and damages are calculated by expert economists.</p>
  <h2>Wage and hour / employment</h2><p>FLSA collective actions and Rule 23 class actions for unpaid wages, overtime, and rest break violations. Individual awards higher than consumer cases because wage loss is concrete. California PAGA adds penalties on top of damages.</p>
  <h2>Product liability / MDL</h2><p>Mass torts involving defective products, pharmaceuticals, or medical devices often proceed as multi-district litigation (MDL). Individual injury severity drives allocation. Settlement values per claimant range from hundreds to millions depending on harm.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-class-action-settlements-work">how settlements work</a> and <a href="/guides/filing-a-class-action-claim">how to file a claim</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
